06508nam a22008775i 9781487575144DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191994onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875751447 a10.3138/97814875751442doi  a(DE-B1597)536958  a(OCoLC)1099529076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aKE8928b.C748 1994eb 7aSOC0600002bisacsh04a364.1/53/097122000aConfronting Sexual Assault :bA Decade of Legal and Social Change /ced. by Julian Roberts, Renata Mohr. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- t1. Sexual Assault in Canada: Recent Developments -- t2. The Struggle to Redefine Rape in the Early 1980s -- t3. Changing Definitions of Sexual Assault: An Analysis of Police Statistics -- t4. The Processing of Child Sexual Abuse Cases -- t5. Effects of Reform Legislation on the Processing of Sexual Assault Cases -- t6. The Judicial Construction of Sexual Assault Offences -- t7. Sexual Assault Sentencing: Leaving Justice to Individual Conscience -- t8. Sexual Assault of Inuit Females: A Comment on 'Cultural Bias' -- t9. Compensation for Women Who Have Been Raped -- t10. Sexual Assault Trials and the Protection of 'Bad Girls': The Battle between the Courts and Parliament -- t11. Seaboyer and Gayme: A Study InEquality -- t12. Redefining Reformism: The Consultations That Shaped Bill C-49 -- t13. Sexual Assault: Future Research Priorities -- tAppendix A. Sexual Assault in Canada: A Bibliography ( 1977-1991) -- tAppendix B. Legal Text of 'Rape Shield' Legislation C-490 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decade since the passage of rape reform legislation in 1983, Canada has witnessed an extraordinary growth in public concern about the pervasive and painful issue of sexual assault. Despite this legislation, society continues to pay the price of coercive sexuality. The essays in this volume address the role that legislative reform can play in reducing and ultimately eliminating those costs.The subjects explored include the origins of the 1983 legislation, recent national trends in criminal justice statistics relating to sexual assault, cultural bias, alternatives to sentencing, and the provision of civil compensation for the victims of sexual assault. Essays also analyse how cases are processed, how judges have constructed sexual assault, and how the level of harm caused is determined. The concluding chapters discuss the struggle between the Courts and Parliament in determining the admissibility of sexual history evidence (before and after the Seaboyer decision) and the consultation process that contributed to the 1992 legislative changes.Several common themes emerge. One is that statutory revisions can effect changes in the behaviour of criminal justice personnel only to a limited extent. Another is the need for explicit guidance in - and perhaps limits on - the exercise of discretion by these personnel in their handling of sexual assault cases. Finally, almost every chapter in this volume stresses that the issue of criminal sexual aggression can be understood and dealt with effectively only with the help of an integrated approach which includes both sociological and legal perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aRapexLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aRapezCanada. 0aSex crimesxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aSex crimeszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sexual Abuse & Harassment.2bisacsh1 aBowland, Adelyn L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyle, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re